{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ALMVQtdPbBu4NNvHj4Eo5w","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→{\n     2→  \"version\": 2,\n     3→  \"step_time_regimes\": [\n     4→    {\n     5→      \"name\": \"decode_only\",\n     6→      \"condition\": {\n     7→        \"feature\": \"prefill_tokens\",\n     8→        \"op\": \"==\",\n     9→        \"value\": 0\n    10→      },\n    11→      \"model\": {\n    12→        \"model_type\": \"linear\",\n    13→        \"intercept\": -37.37132221350058,\n    14→        \"feature_coefficients\": {\n    15→          \"decode_tokens\": 7.951495295146752,\n    16→          \"num_decode_reqs\": 7.951495295147041\n    17→        }\n    18→      }\n    19→    },\n    20→    {\n    21→      \"name\": \"mixed_light\",\n    22→      \"condition\": {\n    23→        \"feature\": \"prefill_tokens\",\n    24→        \"op\": \"<\",\n    25→        \"value\": 256\n    26→      },\n    27→      \"model\": {\n    28→        \"model_type\": \"linear\",\n    29→        \"intercept\": -77.97943712885353,\n    30→        \"feature_coefficients\": {\n    31→          \"prefill_tokens\": 28.707846070521985,\n    32→          \"decode_tokens\": 8.238725686646465,\n    33→          \"num_prefill_reqs\": 48.63455190521838,\n    34→          \"num_decode_reqs\": 8.238725687421233,\n    35→          \"prefill_x_decode\": -0.15969273704853537,\n    36→          \"prefill_sq\": -0.8113619055257316\n    37→        }\n    38→      }\n    39→    }\n    40→  ],\n    41→  \"step_overhead_us\": 3896.7631749593834,\n    42→  \"output_token_processing_time_us\": 0,\n    43→  \"scheduling_processing_time_us\": 0,\n    44→  \"preemption_processing_time_us\": 0\n    45→}"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Vx9FActZvVu6PzWLHbXEX2","session_id":"7ea608f4-4aa5-4264-9119-cf38f8fb2f5c","uuid":"495e1150-612a-48a5-a411-99a561de580e"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01APx6ZPk3ir4S3h3nXXpiat","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Idea 1: Bayesian Calibration — Findings Summary\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-02-27\n     4→**Overall Verdict:** All hypotheses refuted. The 2-regime piecewise-linear approach is structurally weaker than Idea 2's 3-regime ensemble.\n     5→\n     6→---\n     7→\n     8→## Executive Summary\n     9→\n    10→Idea 1 proposed a piecewise-linear StepTime model with two regimes (decode-only vs mixed-batch), ProgressIndex-derived KV features, and joint Bayesian optimization of all 5 LatencyModel methods against BLIS E2E error. Four hypotheses were designed; three were executed (H1, H4, H5) and one was blocked (H2).\n    11→\n    12→**Every executed hypothesis was refuted.** The core structural limitation is the 2-regime split: lumping all mixed-batch steps (1 prefill token through 2000+) into a single linear regime creates too much heterogeneity for a linear model. Additionally, KV features provided zero-to-negative contribution in this formulation, and the approach was worse than Round 1 for workload generalization.\n    13→\n    14→---\n    15→\n    16→## Hypothesis Scorecard\n    17→\n    18→| # | Hypothesis | Target | Result | Status |\n    19→|---|-----------|--------|--------|--------|\n    20→| H1 | Piecewise-linear StepTime (<30% MAPE) | <30% per-step MAPE | **87.4%** | **Refuted** |\n    21→| H2 | Joint BO of all 5 methods (<15% E2E) | <15% E2E mean error | Not run | **Blocked** |\n    22→| H4 | LOMO cross-validation (<80% MAPE) | <80% per-step MAPE | **148.8%** | **Refuted** |\n    23→| H5 | LOWO cross-validation (<40% MAPE) | <40% per-step MAPE | **155.4%** | **Refuted** |\n    24→\n    25→---\n    26→\n    27→## Key Results\n    28→\n    29→### H1: Piecewise-Linear StepTime — Per-Model Quality\n    30→\n    31→The base model achieves 87.4% weighted MAPE across 5 model+TP configurations, barely improving over the 2-feature blackbox baseline (89.7%). Performance varies dramatically by model:\n    32→\n    33→| Model | Piecewise MAPE | Blackbox MAPE | Improvement |\n    34→|-------|---------------|--------------|-------------|\n    35→| Mixtral-8x7B (TP2) | 18.6% | 20.7% | +2.1 pp |\n    36→| Llama-2-7B (TP1) | 38.2% | 40.2% | +2.0 pp |\n    37→| Llama-2-70B-HF (TP4) | 88.4% | 90.6% | +2.2 pp |\n    38→| Llama-2-70B (TP4) | 94.7% | 86.8% | -7.9 pp |\n    39→| CodeLlama-34B (TP2) | 168.5% | 176.9% | +8.4 pp |\n    40→\n    41→**KV features hurt overall** (-3.6 pp) — the model without KV features achieved 83.8% MAPE vs 87.4% with KV. For 2/5 models (7B, Mixtral), Ridge assigned zero weight to KV features. For the 70B models, KV features increased error.\n    42→\n    43→### H4: Cross-Model Transfer (LOMO) — 17x Better than Round 1\n    44→\n    45→| Held-Out Model | MAPE | MSPE | Key Observation |\n    46→|---------------|------|------|----------------|\n    47→| CodeLlama-34B | 53.9% | Mixed | Best fold — 34B interpolates between 7B and 70B |\n    48→| Llama-2-70B | 146.5% | +105%/+177% | Heavily overpredicted |\n    49→| Llama-2-7B | 187.0% | -185%/-205% | **Negative predictions** — catastrophic scale mismatch |\n    50→| Mixtral-8x7B (MoE) | 207.8% | +152%/+312% | Dense-to-MoE transfer fails completely |\n    51→\n    52→Average 148.8% MAPE (target: <80%), but still 17.2x better than Round 1's LOMO baseline (2559.7%). The improvement comes from regime separation, but the model lacks scale normalization needed for cross-architecture transfer.\n    53→\n    54→### H5: Cross-Workload Transfer (LOWO) — Worse than Round 1\n    55→\n    56→| Model | general | codegen | roleplay | Avg |\n    57→|-------|---------|---------|----------|-----|\n    58→| Mixtral | 15.8% | 21.4% | 26.6% | **21.3%** |\n    59→| 34B | 43.4% | 292.4% | 107.2% | 147.7% |\n    60→| 70B | 145.9% | 265.2% | 480.6% | 297.3% |\n    61→| 7B | — | — | — | (no data) |\n    62→\n    63→Grand average 155.4% MAPE (target: <40%), which is 0.7x of Round 1's LOWO (109.7%) — a **regression**. Mixtral is the sole success (21.3%), proving MoE architectures generalize across workloads. Dense models fail because workload-specific batch-composition distributions shift between training and test.\n    64→\n    65→### H2: Bayesian Optimization — Not Run\n    66→\n    67→Blocked because H1's base model (87.4% MAPE) is too inaccurate for BO to compensate. BO can tune overhead and secondary constants but cannot fix batch-composition-dependent prediction errors. The ~66-133 hours of compute is unjustified. Idea 2's comparable test (H3) already showed secondary methods contribute minimally to E2E error.\n    68→\n    69→---\n    70→\n    71→## Root Causes of Failure\n    72→\n    73→### 1. The 2-regime split is structurally insufficient\n    74→\n    75→The decode-only / mixed-batch boundary is too coarse. The mixed-batch regime (22.1% of steps) spans steps with 1 prefill token to 2000+ prefill tokens. This range includes both memory-bound micro-prefills and compute-bound large prefills — fundamentally different operations that a single linear model cannot represent.\n    76→\n    77→**Evidence:** Idea 2's 3-regime split (decode-only / mixed-light / mixed-heavy at 256-token boundary) achieves substantially different MAPE for mixed-light vs mixed-heavy, confirming the heterogeneity.\n    78→\n    79→### 2. KV features require finer regime segmentation to be useful\n    80→\n    81→KV features (kv_sum, kv_max, kv_mean) have extremely high variance (0 to 64,000+) relative to step-time range (70-7,000 us). In the 2-regime formulation:\n    82→- Ridge assigns zero weight to KV features for Mixtral and 7B (features are noise)\n    83→- For 70B models, the tiny KV coefficients amplify noise at extreme KV values\n    84→- The blackbox's `decode_tokens` is a better proxy because it correlates with batch size and has lower variance\n    85→\n    86→With Idea 2's mixed-light/mixed-heavy split, KV features become informative because the regime boundary constrains the feature space.\n    87→\n    88→### 3. Raw linear regression has inherent per-step MAPE limitations\n    89→\n    90→`step.duration_us` captures GPU forward pass only (median ~200-3000 us). The batch-feature-to-time relationship is approximately log-linear, not linear. Raw linear regression:\n    91→- Overpredicts small-batch steps (can produce negative predictions)\n    92→- Underpredicts large-batch steps\n    93→- Achieves high per-step MAPE even when the overhead floor makes E2E accuracy acceptable\n    94→\n    95→This is consistent with Round 2's earlier finding that raw linear per-step MAPE is ~448% but irrelevant for BLIS E2E.\n    96→\n    97→### 4. Cross-model transfer requires scale normalization\n    98→\n    99→LOMO fails because step-time scales differ by 5-10x across models (7B: ~150us, 70B: ~1000us). The linear model learns coefficients scaled for the training models. Without normalizing features by model-specific constants (parameter count, FLOPS per token), the predictions are catastrophically wrong for held-out models at different scales.\n   100→\n   101→### 5. Cross-workload transfer requires feature diversity or nonlinearity\n   102→\n   103→LOWO fails because different workloads create different batch-composition distributions. A linear model on 4 features cannot capture these distributional shifts. Round 1's 30-feature XGBoost performed better (109.7% vs 155.4%) because it had more features and nonlinear capacity to absorb distribution shifts.\n   104→\n   105→---\n   106→\n   107→## Comparison with Idea 2 (3-Regime Ensemble)\n   108→\n   109→| Metric | Idea 1 (2-regime) | Idea 2 (3-regime) | Winner |\n   110→|--------|-------------------|-------------------|--------|\n   111→| H1 per-step MAPE | 87.4% | Comparable (per-model) | Idea 2 |\n   112→| KV feature contribution | -3.6 pp (harmful) | Positive (mixed-heavy KV helps) | Idea 2 |\n   113→| LOMO avg MAPE | 148.8% | (refuted at similar level) | Comparable |\n   114→| LOWO avg MAPE | 155.4% | (refuted at ~similar level) | Comparable |\n   115→| Feature count per regime | 4 | 7-8 | Idea 2 |\n   116→| Regime boundary | Binary (prefill=0 vs >0) | Ternary (0 / <256 / >=256) | Idea 2 |\n   117→\n   118→**Verdict:** Idea 2's 3-regime approach is strictly better. The additional regime boundary and richer feature set provide meaningful improvements, especially for mixed-batch prediction and KV feature utilization.\n   119→\n   120→---\n   121→\n   122→## Surprises and Positive Findings\n   123→\n   124→Despite overall refutation, several valuable insights emerged:\n   125→\n   126→1. **Mixtral generalizes exceptionally well.** Both LOMO (Fold 4 aside) and LOWO (21.3% avg) show that MoE architectures have more regular step-time scaling that transfers across contexts. A single Mixtral StepML model can serve any workload type.\n   127→\n   128→2. **LOMO interpolation works for 34B.** Holding out CodeLlama-34B (which falls between 7B and 70B in scale) yields 53.9% MAPE — suggesting that cross-model transfer via interpolation is feasible with proper scale normalization.\n   129→\n   130→3. **Per-model overhead is consistent with Round 2 findings.** The overhead values (3.9ms for 7B, 6.7ms for 34B, 8.0-8.2ms for 70B, 9.1ms for Mixtral) match prior observations, providing independent validation.\n   131→\n   132→4. **\"General\" workload is the easiest holdout.** In LOWO, holding out the \"general\" workload yields the lowest average MAPE (68.4%), likely because \"general\" has the most diverse batch compositions (averaging effect), making it the most representative of a mixture of training workloads.\n   133→\n   134→---\n   135→\n   136→## Recommendations\n   137→\n   138→### For StepML Research\n   139→\n   140→1. **Abandon the 2-regime piecewise-linear approach.** The 3-regime split (Idea 2) is strictly better and should be the foundation for further work.\n   141→2. **Investigate feature normalization for LOMO.** The 34B interpolation result (53.9%) suggests that dividing features by model-specific constants (parameter count, FLOPS per token) could make cross-model transfer viable.\n   142→3. **Explore MoE-specific models.** Mixtral's consistent success across all experiments suggests that MoE architecture warrants a dedicated StepML model family.\n   143→4. **Do not invest in BO until per-step quality improves.** Joint BO cannot compensate for structural model errors. Focus on improving the base StepTime model first.\n   144→\n   145→### For BLIS Deployment\n   146→\n   147→1. **Use per-model StepML coefficients** — cross-model and cross-workload transfer are not production-ready.\n   148→2. **The overhead floor (`max(overhead, compute)`) remains the primary accuracy mechanism.** Per-step MAPE is poor, but the overhead floor makes E2E accuracy acceptable for standard workloads.\n   149→3. **Ship Mixtral with a single universal model.** Its LOWO results (21.3%) justify deploying one model for all Mixtral workloads.\n   150→\n   151→---\n   152→\n   153→## Data and Artifacts\n   154→\n   155→| Hypothesis | Output Directory | Key Files |\n   156→|-----------|-----------------|-----------|\n   157→| H1 | `h1-piecewise-steptime/output/` | `piecewise_results.csv`, `piecewise_summary.json`, `artifacts/*.json` |\n   158→| H2 | `h2-joint-bo-calibration/output/` | (not run — script ready at `bo_calibrate.py`) |\n   159→| H4 | `h4-model-generalization/output/` | `lomo_per_step_results.csv`, `lomo_summary.json`, `lomo_artifacts/*.json` |\n   160→| H5 | `h5-workload-generalization/output/` | `lowo_per_step_results.csv`, `lowo_summary.json`, `lowo_artifacts/*.json` |\n   161→\n   162→## Reproducing All Experiments\n   163→\n   164→```bash\n   165→# H1: Base model training (~5 min)\n   166→cd hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/idea-1-bayesian-calibration/h1-piecewise-steptime && ./run.sh\n   167→\n   168→# H4: LOMO cross-validation (~15 min)\n   169→cd hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/idea-1-bayesian-calibration/h4-model-generalization && ./run.sh\n   170→\n   171→# H5: LOWO cross-validation (~15 min)\n   172→cd hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/idea-1-bayesian-calibration/h5-workload-generalization && ./run.sh\n   173→\n   174→# H2: BO calibration (~66-133 hours, not recommended)\n   175→cd hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/idea-1-bayesian-calibration/h2-joint-bo-calibration && ./run.sh\n   176→```\n   177→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Vx9FActZvVu6PzWLHbXEX2","session_id":"7ea608f4-4aa5-4264-9119-cf38f8fb2f5c","uuid":"e2ecfe52-a7ae-4a9c-b7f7-6f28307de523"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Vpwowv2dyhSu5WViDJNDBf","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→{\n     2→  \"version\": 2,\n     3→  \"step_time_regimes\": [\n     4→    {\n     5→      \"name\": \"decode_only\",\n     6→      \"condition\": {\n     7→        \"feature\": \"prefill_tokens\",\n     8→        \"op\": \"==\",\n     9→        \"value\": 0\n    10→      },\n    11→      \"model\": {\n    12→        \"model_type\": \"linear\",\n    13→        \"intercept\": -36.65650017459026,\n    14→        \"feature_coefficients\": {\n    15→          \"decode_tokens\": 15.842770225854478\n    16→        }\n    17→      }\n    18→    },\n    19→    {\n    20→      \"name\": \"mixed_batch\",\n    21→      \"condition\": null,\n    22→      \"model\": {\n    23→        \"model_type\": \"linear\",\n    24→        \"intercept\": 77.40390345846424,\n    25→        \"feature_coefficients\": {\n    26→          \"prefill_tokens\": 0.4850157535630972,\n    27→          \"decode_tokens\": 15.74901534539433,\n    28→          \"prefill_x_decode\": -0.019980966674227878\n    29→        }\n    30→      }\n    31→    }\n    32→  ],\n    33→  \"step_overhead_us\": 3896.7631749593834,\n    34→  \"output_token_processing_time_us\": 0,\n    35→  \"scheduling_processing_time_us\": 0,\n    36→  \"preemption_processing_time_us\": 0\n    37→}"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Vx9FActZvVu6PzWLHbXEX2","session_id":"7ea608f4-4aa5-4264-9119-cf38f8fb2f5c","uuid":"6bc999f1-b82e-4754-a3d3-27793b530c25"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Y59Tos6vvr49NxQUe2Marg","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Idea 2: Regime-Switching Ensemble — Findings Summary\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-02-27\n     4→**Data:** 77,816 steps from 10 experiments (4 models x 3 workloads; no reasoning workloads in this dataset)\n     5→**Models:** Llama-2-7B (TP1), Llama-2-70B (TP4), CodeLlama-34B (TP2), Mixtral-8x7B (TP2)\n     6→**Workloads:** general, codegen, roleplay\n     7→\n     8→---\n     9→\n    10→## Executive Summary\n    11→\n    12→Idea 2's regime-switching Ridge ensemble was designed to exploit the insight that batch computation falls into distinct regimes (decode-only, mixed-light, mixed-heavy) with different feature-performance relationships. The approach uses ProgressIndex-derived KV features to capture per-request memory footprint — a key missing signal identified in Round 1.\n    13→\n    14→**Bottom line:** On the current ground-truth data (10 experiments, 77K steps), Idea 2 fails to meet its primary targets. Per-step MAPE is 64.4% (target was <15%), BLIS E2E error is 427.8% (target was <10%), and generalization tests both fail. However, ITL prediction remains reasonable at 33.6%, and LOMO shows a 23.6x improvement over Round 1's catastrophic baseline. The results point to specific fixable problems (KV feature instability, workload spec generation for TTFT) rather than a fundamental flaw in the approach.\n    15→\n    16→---\n    17→\n    18→## Hypothesis Results\n    19→\n    20→| # | Hypothesis | Status | Key Metric | Target | Actual |\n    21→|---|-----------|--------|-----------|--------|--------|\n    22→| H1 | Regime Ridge per-step MAPE | **Not met** | Weighted MAPE | <15% | 64.4% |\n    23→| H2 | BLIS E2E validation | **Not met** | Mean E2E error | <10% | 427.8% |\n    24→| H3 | Secondary method calibration | **Refuted** | E2E improvement | >=5pp | 0.0pp |\n    25→| H4 | LOMO (cross-model) | **Refuted** | Avg MAPE | <80% | 108.6% |\n    26→| H5 | LOWO (cross-workload) | **Refuted** | Avg MAPE | <25% | 117.4% |\n    27→\n    28→---\n    29→\n    30→## H1: Regime-Specific Ridge Training\n    31→\n    32→### Per-Model Step Overhead\n    33→\n    34→Step duration in training data captures GPU forward pass only. The real step cycle time includes CPU overhead (scheduling, sync, memory management). Overhead is derived from ground-truth ITL:\n    35→\n    36→| Model | Overhead (us) |\n    37→|-------|--------------|\n    38→| Llama-2-7B (TP1) | 3,897 |\n    39→| CodeLlama-34B (TP2) | 6,673 |\n    40→| Llama-2-70B (TP4) | 8,029-8,203 |\n    41→| Mixtral-8x7B (TP2) | 9,125 |\n    42→\n    43→### Regime Distribution\n    44→\n    45→| Regime | Steps | Share |\n    46→|--------|-------|-------|\n    47→| decode_only (prefill == 0) | 60,613 | 77.9% |\n    48→| mixed_light (0 < prefill < 256) | 17,129 | 22.0% |\n    49→| mixed_heavy (prefill >= 256) | 74 | 0.1% |\n    50→\n    51→Mixed-heavy has only 74 steps — effectively untestable. This is a key difference from the HYPOTHESIS.md expectation of ~4.4% (~5,400 steps), indicating the new ground-truth data has fundamentally different prefill characteristics.\n    52→\n    53→### Per-Model Regime MAPE (Test Set)\n    54→\n    55→| Model | Weighted MAPE | decode_only | mixed_light | Best alpha |\n    56→|-------|--------------|-------------|-------------|------------|\n    57→| Llama-2-7B (TP1) | **36.2%** | 36.6% (r=0.530) | 32.4% (r=0.590) | 1000/0.01 |\n    58→| Mixtral-8x7B (TP2) | **16.6%** | 18.3% (r=0.610) | 13.4% (r=0.872) | 0.01/0.01 |\n    59→| CodeLlama-34B (TP2) | **99.2%** | 65.8% (r=0.785) | 179.9% (r=0.714) | 1000/0.01 |\n    60→| Llama-2-70B-HF (TP4) | **84.4%** | 91.7% (r=0.702) | 67.9% (r=0.697) | 0.01/1000 |\n    61→| Llama-2-70B (TP4) | **93.3%** | 112.2% (r=0.854) | 59.3% (r=0.758) | 1000/1000 |\n    62→\n    63→### Model Comparison\n    64→\n    65→| Model Type | Weighted MAPE |\n    66→|-----------|--------------|\n    67→| Regime-specific Ridge (with KV) | **64.4%** |\n    68→| Single global Ridge (all features) | 93.5% |\n    69→| Blackbox baseline (2 features) | **46.9%** |\n    70→| Regime Ridge (no KV features) | **43.9%** |\n    71→\n    72→### KV Feature Ablation: Negative Contribution\n    73→\n    74→KV features **hurt** per-step MAPE by 20.5 percentage points (64.4% with KV vs. 43.9% without). Per-model breakdown:\n    75→\n    76→| Model | With KV | Without KV | Delta |\n    77→|-------|---------|-----------|-------|\n    78→| Llama-2-7B | 36.2% | 30.1% | +6.1pp worse |\n    79→| Mixtral-8x7B | 16.6% | 22.0% | -5.4pp better |\n    80→| CodeLlama-34B | 99.2% | 55.5% | +43.7pp worse |\n    81→| Llama-2-70B-HF | 84.4% | 48.2% | +36.2pp worse |\n    82→| Llama-2-70B | 93.3% | 68.3% | +25.0pp worse |\n    83→\n    84→KV features only help Mixtral. For all dense models, KV features degrade performance. The numerical overflow warnings during Ridge training (divide-by-zero, overflow in matmul) confirm that KV feature magnitudes (kv_sum up to 64,000+) cause coefficient instability in raw linear space.\n    85→\n    86→### Diagnosis\n    87→\n    88→1. **Mixed-heavy regime is empty** (74 steps vs. expected ~5,400). The 256-token prefill threshold sees almost no steps. This means the 3-regime split collapses to 2 effective regimes.\n    89→2. **KV features cause numerical instability.** Large kv_sum values produce overflow during Ridge CV grid search. Alpha=1000 often wins for large models, indicating severe regularization is needed to tame unstable coefficients.\n    90→3. **The blackbox 2-feature baseline outperforms all KV-augmented models.** This suggests the KV features as implemented add noise rather than signal — possibly because ProgressIndex KV proxies are poorly correlated with actual batch-level compute cost in this dataset.\n    91→\n    92→---\n    93→\n    94→## H2: BLIS E2E Validation\n    95→\n    96→### Per-Experiment Results\n    97→\n    98→| Experiment | E2E Error | TTFT Error | ITL Error |\n    99→|-----------|-----------|------------|-----------|\n   100→| 7b-roleplay | 52.5% | 78.4% | **4.0%** |\n   101→| 70b-general | 182.7% | 12,567% | 23.5% |\n   102→| 70b-hf-codegen | 55.7% | 77.7% | **10.7%** |\n   103→| 70b-roleplay | 55.6% | 77.9% | **10.3%** |\n   104→| mixtral-codegen | 51.5% | 76.5% | **2.1%** |\n   105→| mixtral-general | 554.6% | 44,464% | **8.7%** |\n   106→| mixtral-roleplay | 50.8% | 77.2% | **0.7%** |\n   107→| 34b-general | 2,901.1% | 230,931% | 80.3% |\n   108→| 34b-codegen | 370.2% | 30,425% | 95.9% |\n   109→| 34b-roleplay | **3.3%** | 282.7% | 100.1% |\n   110→\n   111→### Aggregate Metrics\n   112→\n   113→| Metric | Mean | Experiments <10% |\n   114→|--------|------|-----------------|\n   115→| E2E error | 427.8% | 1/10 (34b-roleplay) |\n   116→| TTFT error | 31,906% | 0/10 |\n   117→| ITL error | 33.6% | 5/10 |\n   118→\n   119→### Pattern Analysis\n   120→\n   121→- **ITL is the best metric** (33.6% mean, 5/10 under 10%). ITL directly reflects step-time prediction quality + overhead floor, confirming the core modeling approach works for decode-dominant workloads.\n   122→- **TTFT errors are catastrophic** (thousands to hundreds-of-thousands percent). This indicates the BLIS simulation's prefill + queueing timing is fundamentally mismatched with the ground truth. The workload spec generation or request injection timing may be wrong.\n   123→- **\"general\" workloads consistently worst** (70b-general 182.7%, mixtral-general 554.6%, 34b-general 2901.1%). The \"general\" workload likely has longer prefill sequences and more variable batch dynamics.\n   124→- **CodeLlama-34B is the worst model** across all metrics. Per-step MAPE for 34b was already 99.2% (worst in H1).\n   125→\n   126→---\n   127→\n   128→## H3: Secondary Method Calibration\n   129→\n   130→### Extracted Constants\n   131→\n   132→| Model | Queue-to-Schedule (us) | Schedule-to-First-Token (us) |\n   133→|-------|----------------------|---------------------------|\n   134→| Llama-2-7B (TP1) | 202 (p25=187, p75=219) | 15,884 |\n   135→| Llama-2-70B (TP4) | 415 (p25=265, p75=550) | 40,869 |\n   136→| Llama-2-70B-HF (TP4) | 281 (p25=220, p75=316) | 37,372 |\n   137→| CodeLlama-34B (TP2) | 291 (p25=246, p75=510) | 30,100 |\n   138→| Mixtral-8x7B (TP2) | 353 (p25=275, p75=577) | 37,952 |\n   139→\n   140→### Ablation Result\n   141→\n   142→| Config | Mean E2E | Mean TTFT | Mean ITL |\n   143→|--------|----------|-----------|----------|\n   144→| A: StepTime-only | 427.8% | 31,905.8% | 33.6% |\n   145→| B: + Secondary methods | 427.8% | 31,905.7% | 33.6% |\n   146→| **Delta** | **+0.0pp** | **+0.0pp** | **+0.0pp** |\n   147→\n   148→**Verdict: REFUTED.** The secondary method constants (200-400 us) are negligible compared to E2E errors of hundreds to thousands of percent. When the dominant error source (StepTime or workload spec) is off by orders of magnitude, microsecond-level corrections cannot matter.\n   149→\n   150→---\n   151→\n   152→## H4: LOMO (Leave-One-Model-Out)\n   153→\n   154→### Per-Fold Results\n   155→\n   156→| Fold | Held-Out Model | Per-Step MAPE | BLIS E2E Mean |\n   157→|------|---------------|---------------|---------------|\n   158→| 1 | CodeLlama-34B | 63.4% | 657.0% |\n   159→| 2 | Llama-2-70B | 197.6% | 797.6% |\n   160→| 3 | Llama-2-7B | 41.2% | BLIS failed |\n   161→| 4 | Mixtral-8x7B | 132.3% | 253.7% |\n   162→\n   163→**Average LOMO MAPE: 108.6%** (target: <80%) — **REFUTED**\n   164→\n   165→### Per-Regime MAPE (Across Folds)\n   166→\n   167→| Regime | Average MAPE | Range |\n   168→|--------|-------------|-------|\n   169→| decode_only | 88.9% | 27.8-200.4% |\n   170→| mixed_light | 185.7% | 55.0-320.6% |\n   171→| mixed_heavy | 243.1% | 67.5-473.9% |\n   172→\n   173→### Comparison to Round 1\n   174→\n   175→- Round 1 LOMO: 2,559.7% average MAPE\n   176→- Round 2 LOMO: 108.6% average MAPE\n   177→- **Improvement: 23.6x** (significant, but still above 80% threshold)\n   178→\n   179→### Diagnosis\n   180→\n   181→The 70B fold is the worst (197.6%) because 70B is the largest model with highest absolute step times. Cross-model transfer fails because step-time scale is model-dependent (determined by parameter count and TP degree). The Mixtral fold (132.3%) confirms that dense-to-MoE transfer remains challenging due to fundamentally different compute scaling.\n   182→\n   183→---\n   184→\n   185→## H5: LOWO (Leave-One-Workload-Out)\n   186→\n   187→### Per-Model LOWO MAPE\n   188→\n   189→| Model | Avg MAPE | Worst Fold |\n   190→|-------|----------|-----------|\n   191→| 7b | 25.6% | roleplay (31.1%) |\n   192→| 34b | 131.0% | roleplay (183.5%) |\n   193→| 70b | 293.8% | roleplay (420.0%) |\n   194→| Mixtral | 19.1% | roleplay (23.9%) |\n   195→\n   196→**Grand average LOWO MAPE: 117.4%** (target: <25%) — **REFUTED**\n   197→\n   198→### Per-Workload MAPE (Across Models)\n   199→\n   200→| Held-Out Workload | Avg MAPE | Range |\n   201→|-------------------|----------|-------|\n   202→| codegen | 123.1% | 18.7-265.1% |\n   203→| general | 67.4% | 14.8-145.4% |\n   204→| roleplay | 161.7% | 23.9-420.0% |\n   205→\n   206→### BLIS E2E on Held-Out Workloads\n   207→\n   208→| Held-Out Workload | Mean E2E Error | Mean ITL Error |\n   209→|-------------------|---------------|----------------|\n   210→| codegen | 163.5% | 36.8% |\n   211→| general | 273.0% | 16.4% |\n   212→| roleplay | 36.4% | 36.7% |\n   213→\n   214→### Comparison to Round 1\n   215→\n   216→- Round 1 LOWO: 109.7% average MAPE\n   217→- Round 2 LOWO: 117.4% average MAPE\n   218→- **Improvement: 0.9x** (no improvement — slightly worse)\n   219→\n   220→### Diagnosis\n   221→\n   222→Workload generalization is comparable to Round 1. The regime structure was expected to provide workload-agnostic computation modeling, but LOWO MAPE actually regressed slightly. The 70B model dominates the error average (293.8%), suggesting that for large models with complex batch dynamics, workload distribution shifts have outsized impact on predictions.\n   223→\n   224→---\n   225→\n   226→## Cross-Cutting Findings\n   227→\n   228→### 1. KV Features Are Counter-Productive in Raw Linear Space\n   229→\n   230→The central thesis of Idea 2 was that ProgressIndex-derived KV features would improve per-step prediction. On this ground-truth data, the opposite is true: KV features degrade per-step MAPE from 43.9% to 64.4%. The root cause is numerical instability — kv_sum values reaching 64,000+ cause Ridge coefficient overflow when alpha is small. Only Mixtral benefits from KV features (-5.4pp), possibly because its MoE architecture has a different KV-to-compute relationship.\n   231→\n   232→**Implication:** KV features need either (a) normalization/scaling before regression, (b) log-transform of features (not target), or (c) a non-linear model that handles large feature ranges gracefully.\n   233→\n   234→### 2. Mixed-Heavy Regime Is Empty\n   235→\n   236→Only 74 of 77,816 steps (0.1%) fall in the mixed-heavy regime (prefill >= 256). The original hypothesis expected ~4.4% based on 16 experiments with 4 workloads. The current 10-experiment dataset (3 workloads, no reasoning) has very few long-prefill batches. The 3-regime design is effectively a 2-regime design on this data.\n   237→\n   238→### 3. TTFT Errors Indicate Systematic Workload Spec or Simulation Mismatch\n   239→\n   240→TTFT errors of 31,906% cannot be explained by per-step model inaccuracy. These errors point to a mismatch in how the BLIS simulation generates/schedules requests vs. how the real system operates. Likely causes include:\n   241→- Workload spec generation (`build_workload_spec`) producing request arrival patterns that don't match the ground truth\n   242→- BLIS request queueing behavior differing from real vLLM queueing\n   243→- Prefill scheduling in BLIS (chunked prefill, request admission) not matching the real system's behavior\n   244→\n   245→### 4. ITL Remains the Most Accurate Metric\n   246→\n   247→Despite the per-step model limitations, ITL error is 33.6% mean with 5/10 experiments under 10%. This confirms that the overhead floor mechanism (`max(overhead, compute)`) effectively handles the decode-dominated continuous batching regime. The step-time model's accuracy matters less when the overhead floor dominates — which it does for small-to-medium batch sizes.\n   248→\n   249→### 5. CodeLlama-34B Is Consistently the Worst Model\n   250→\n   251→34B shows the highest per-step MAPE (99.2%), worst BLIS E2E (2,901% for general), and high generalization errors. This model may have batch dynamics that differ significantly from the Llama-2 family. Investigation into 34B-specific step-time distributions and batch size patterns is warranted.\n   252→\n   253→### 6. \"General\" Workloads Are Consistently Hard\n   254→\n   255→Across H2, the \"general\" workload produces the worst E2E errors for every model (182.7%, 554.6%, 2,901.1%). The \"general\" workload likely has more diverse batch compositions and longer prefill sequences, pushing the model into poorly-covered regions of the feature space.\n   256→\n   257→---\n   258→\n   259→## Recommendations for Next Steps\n   260→\n   261→1. **Fix KV feature scaling.** Normalize KV features (e.g., kv_sum / max_kv_blocks, kv_mean / max_seq_len) before regression, or use StandardScaler within the Ridge pipeline.\n   262→\n   263→2. **Investigate TTFT errors.** The 31,906% mean TTFT error is the dominant contributor to E2E error. Diagnose whether the workload spec, BLIS request injection, or prefill scheduling is the root cause.\n   264→\n   265→3. **Lower the mixed-heavy threshold or drop it.** With only 74 steps in mixed-heavy, consider a 2-regime model (decode-only vs. any-mixed) or lower the threshold to 64 or 128 tokens.\n   266→\n   267→4. **Investigate 34B-specific dynamics.** CodeLlama-34B accounts for disproportionate error. Check if its batch size distribution, step-time distribution, or KV utilization patterns differ qualitatively from other models.\n   268→\n   269→5. **Consider feature scaling for large models.** The 70B and 34B models show much higher MAPE than 7B and Mixtral. This may be because absolute feature values (kv_sum, decode_tokens) scale with model capacity, and raw linear regression cannot handle the scale differences without normalization.\n   270→\n   271→---\n   272→\n   273→## Output Artifacts\n   274→\n   275→| Hypothesis | Output Directory | Key Files |\n   276→|-----------|-----------------|-----------|\n   277→| H1 | `h1-kv-regime-models/output/` | `regime_ridge_results.csv`, `artifacts/*.json` |\n   278→| H2 | `h2-blis-e2e-validation/output/` | `e2e_validation_regime.csv`, `e2e_summary_regime.json` |\n   279→| H3 | `h3-secondary-method-calibration/output/` | `ablation_comparison.csv`, `ablation_summary.json`, `secondary_constants.json` |\n   280→| H4 | `h4-model-generalization/output/` | `lomo_per_step_results.csv`, `lomo_blis_e2e_results.csv`, `lomo_summary.json` |\n   281→| H5 | `h5-workload-generalization/output/` | `lowo_per_step_results.csv`, `lowo_blis_e2e_results.csv`, `lowo_summary.json` |\n   282→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Vx9FActZvVu6PzWLHbXEX2","session_id":"7ea608f4-4aa5-4264-9119-cf38f8fb2f5c","uuid":"46ba2350-450f-4d6d-b860-f77ccf1b960c"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Skny9GBHHyXfxSf6B7LWKN","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# StepML Round 2: Findings Summary\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-02-27\n     4→**Branch:** `stepml-experiments`\n     5→**Scope:** Two ideas tested across 10 experiments (4 models x 3 workloads, no reasoning). Both ideas extended Round 1's per-step modeling to include BLIS E2E validation, per-request KV features (ProgressIndex-derived), and generalization testing.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## 1. Problem Recap\n    10→\n    11→Achieve **<10% workload-level E2E mean error** across 12 experiments (4 models x 3 workloads) by improving any or all of the 5 `LatencyModel` methods. The baseline to beat is **115.0% mean E2E error** from per-model linear regression.\n    12→\n    13→Round 1 established that per-experiment XGBoost achieves 34% per-step MAPE but never validated through BLIS E2E simulation. Round 2's mandate was to close that loop: validate through BLIS, add per-request KV features, and test generalization.\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→## 2. What We Tried\n    18→\n    19→### Idea 1: Bayesian Calibration (2-Regime Piecewise Linear)\n    20→\n    21→**Approach:** Split steps into 2 regimes (decode-only vs mixed-batch), fit Ridge regression per regime with ProgressIndex-derived KV features (kv_sum, kv_max, kv_mean), and plan to jointly calibrate all 5 LatencyModel methods via Bayesian optimization.\n    22→\n    23→| Sub-Hypothesis | Target | Result | Status |\n    24→|---|---|---|---|\n    25→| H1: Piecewise-linear StepTime | <30% per-step MAPE | **87.4%** | **Refuted** |\n    26→| H2: Joint Bayesian optimization | <15% E2E mean | Not run | **Blocked** (H1 too inaccurate) |\n    27→| H4: LOMO cross-validation | <80% per-step MAPE | **148.8%** | **Refuted** |\n    28→| H5: LOWO cross-validation | <40% per-step MAPE | **155.4%** | **Refuted** |\n    29→\n    30→### Idea 2: Regime-Switching Ensemble (3-Regime Ridge)\n    31→\n    32→**Approach:** Split steps into 3 regimes (decode-only / mixed-light with prefill<256 / mixed-heavy with prefill>=256), fit Ridge per regime with KV features, validate through BLIS E2E simulation, and calibrate secondary LatencyModel methods from ground-truth lifecycle data.\n    33→\n    34→| Sub-Hypothesis | Target | Result | Status |\n    35→|---|---|---|---|\n    36→| H1: Regime Ridge per-step MAPE | <15% weighted | **64.4%** | **Not met** |\n    37→| H2: BLIS E2E validation | <10% mean | **427.8%** | **Not met** |\n    38→| H3: Secondary method calibration | >=5pp E2E gain | **0.0pp** | **Refuted** |\n    39→| H4: LOMO (cross-model) | <80% avg MAPE | **108.6%** | **Refuted** |\n    40→| H5: LOWO (cross-workload) | <25% avg MAPE | **117.4%** | **Refuted** |\n    41→\n    42→---\n    43→\n    44→## 3. What Worked\n    45→\n    46→### 3.1 Overhead Floor Mechanism (Best Single Contribution)\n    47→\n    48→The `max(overhead, compute)` step-time floor is the most effective accuracy mechanism discovered. Per-model overhead constants:\n    49→\n    50→| Model | Overhead (us) |\n    51→|---|---|\n    52→| Llama-2-7B (TP1) | 3,897 |\n    53→| CodeLlama-34B (TP2) | 6,673 |\n    54→| Llama-2-70B (TP4) | 8,029–8,203 |\n    55→| Mixtral-8x7B (TP2) | 9,125 |\n    56→\n    57→The overhead floor handles the decode-dominated regime (77.9% of steps) by clamping small-batch predictions to the real cycle time. This mechanism alone produces **5/10 experiments with ITL <10%**, proving that for decode-dominant workloads, the overhead floor is more important than the regression model.\n    58→\n    59→### 3.2 ITL Prediction (33.6% Mean, 5/10 Under 10%)\n    60→\n    61→ITL directly reflects step-time + overhead quality. Per-experiment ITL:\n    62→\n    63→| Experiment | ITL Error |\n    64→|---|---|\n    65→| mixtral-roleplay | **0.7%** |\n    66→| mixtral-codegen | **2.1%** |\n    67→| 7b-roleplay | **4.0%** |\n    68→| mixtral-general | **8.7%** |\n    69→| 70b-hf-codegen | **10.7%** |\n    70→| 70b-roleplay | **10.3%** |\n    71→| 70b-general | 23.5% |\n    72→| 34b-general | 80.3% |\n    73→| 34b-codegen | 95.9% |\n    74→| 34b-roleplay | 100.1% |\n    75→\n    76→The 7B and Mixtral models are essentially solved for ITL. The 70B models are close. CodeLlama-34B is the sole outlier.\n    77→\n    78→### 3.3 LOMO Improvement: 23.6x Over Round 1\n    79→\n    80→Round 2 LOMO: 108.6% avg MAPE vs Round 1 LOMO: 2,559.7%. The regime structure plus per-request KV features dramatically improve cross-model transfer, even though the absolute target (<80%) was not met. The 34B holdout fold (63.4% MAPE) shows that interpolation between model scales is feasible.\n    81→\n    82→### 3.4 Mixtral Generalizes Exceptionally Well\n    83→\n    84→Mixtral is consistently the best-performing model across all metrics:\n    85→- Per-step MAPE: 16.6% (best of all models)\n    86→- LOWO: 19.1% avg (below 25% target)\n    87→- ITL: 0.7%, 2.1%, 8.7% (all under 10%)\n    88→\n    89→MoE architectures appear to have more regular compute scaling. A single universal Mixtral model works across all workloads.\n    90→\n    91→### 3.5 Per-Model Overhead Constants Are Stable\n    92→\n    93→Overhead values derived independently in Round 2 match values from earlier Round 2 analysis, confirming they are stable properties of the model+GPU+TP configuration rather than workload-dependent artifacts.\n    94→\n    95→---\n    96→\n    97→## 4. What Failed and Why\n    98→\n    99→### 4.1 KV Features Are Counter-Productive in Raw Linear Space\n   100→\n   101→**The central thesis of Round 2 — that ProgressIndex-derived KV features would improve prediction — was refuted.**\n   102→\n   103→Both ideas showed KV features *degrade* per-step accuracy:\n   104→- Idea 1: +3.6pp worse (87.4% with KV vs 83.8% without)\n   105→- Idea 2: +20.5pp worse (64.4% with KV vs 43.9% without)\n   106→\n   107→**Root cause:** KV feature magnitudes (kv_sum ranging 0 to 64,000+) cause Ridge coefficient instability. Small Ridge alpha values amplify noise from extreme KV values; large alpha values suppress all KV signal. Only Mixtral benefited from KV features (-5.4pp), likely due to its MoE architecture's different KV-to-compute relationship.\n   108→\n   109→**This does NOT mean KV features are useless — it means raw linear regression cannot handle their dynamic range.** Feature scaling (StandardScaler), log-transform, or nonlinear models would likely fix this.\n   110→\n   111→### 4.2 TTFT Errors Are Catastrophic (31,906% Mean)\n   112→\n   113→TTFT errors of thousands to hundreds-of-thousands percent indicate a systematic mismatch between BLIS's request lifecycle and the real system, not a step-time modeling problem. The TTFT error is the dominant contributor to E2E error (427.8%). Likely causes:\n   114→- Workload spec generation producing mismatched request arrival patterns\n   115→- BLIS prefill/queueing behavior diverging from real vLLM scheduling\n   116→- Request injection timing not matching ground-truth arrival distribution\n   117→\n   118→### 4.3 Mixed-Heavy Regime Is Empty\n   119→\n   120→Only 74/77,816 steps (0.1%) have prefill >= 256 tokens. The 3-regime design effectively collapses to 2 regimes on this dataset (which excludes reasoning workloads). The expected ~4.4% share from the 16-experiment Round 1 data does not hold for the 10-experiment Round 2 data.\n   121→\n   122→### 4.4 Secondary Methods Contribute Zero\n   123→\n   124→H3's ablation showed that calibrating SchedulingProcessingTime and QueueingTime constants (200–400 us) produced **exactly 0.0 percentage points** of E2E improvement. When the dominant error source (StepTime or workload spec) is off by orders of magnitude, microsecond-level corrections are invisible.\n   125→\n   126→### 4.5 CodeLlama-34B Is Consistently the Worst Model\n   127→\n   128→34B shows the highest per-step MAPE (99.2%), worst BLIS E2E (2,901% for general), and outlier LOMO/LOWO errors. This model may have batch dynamics that differ significantly from the Llama-2 family.\n   129→\n   130→### 4.6 Cross-Workload Transfer Did Not Improve\n   131→\n   132→LOWO regressed slightly from Round 1 (117.4% vs 109.7%). The regime structure was expected to provide workload-agnostic modeling but did not. The 70B model dominates the error (293.8%), suggesting large-model workload shifts have outsized impact.\n   133→\n   134→---\n   135→\n   136→## 5. Data Characteristics Learned (Round 2)\n   137→\n   138→### 5.1 Step Duration vs Cycle Time\n   139→\n   140→`step.duration_us` captures GPU forward pass only (~70–7,000 us). Real step cycle time includes CPU overhead: scheduling, synchronization, memory management. The overhead ranges 4–9ms per model and is derived from: `GT_ITL_us - mean_compute_us`.\n   141→\n   142→### 5.2 Overhead Integration Approaches (All Tested)\n   143→\n   144→| Approach | Result |\n   145→|---|---|\n   146→| Additive (compute + overhead) | Phase transition — under-capacity to overload with no stable point |\n   147→| Log-space cycle time | Exponential amplification — batch-size coefficients get multiplied, not added |\n   148→| **Max floor (best)** | `step_time = max(overhead, compute)` — handles memory-bound→compute-bound crossover |\n   149→| Floor + cap | `max(overhead, min(compute, 3*overhead))` prevents exponential blowup from expm1 |\n   150→\n   151→### 5.3 Log-Space (expm1) Pitfalls\n   152→\n   153→- KV features: coefficient 0.0001 x 64,000 = 6.4 in log-space → 601x multiplier\n   154→- Prefill tokens: coefficient 0.06 x 500 = 30 in log-space → exp(30) = absurd\n   155→- Safe ONLY for decode-only batches with small coefficients\n   156→\n   157→### 5.4 Raw Linear for BLIS E2E\n   158→\n   159→Use `use_log_target=False` for all regimes destined for BLIS consumption. Per-step MAPE is ~448% but irrelevant — the overhead floor handles decode-dominated steps, and the linear model only matters for large-batch compute-bound steps.\n   160→\n   161→### 5.5 Phase Distribution (10-Experiment Dataset)\n   162→\n   163→| Regime | Steps | Share |\n   164→|---|---|---|\n   165→| Decode-only (prefill = 0) | 60,613 | 77.9% |\n   166→| Mixed-light (0 < prefill < 256) | 17,129 | 22.0% |\n   167→| Mixed-heavy (prefill >= 256) | 74 | 0.1% |\n   168→\n   169→### 5.6 Step Data Is ~10% Sampled\n   170→\n   171→Not every step is logged in lifecycle data. Step observations come from OpenTelemetry tracing at ~10% sample rate.\n   172→\n   173→---\n   174→\n   175→## 6. Comparison of Ideas\n   176→\n   177→| Metric | Idea 1 (2-regime) | Idea 2 (3-regime) | Winner |\n   178→|---|---|---|---|\n   179→| Per-step MAPE (with KV) | 87.4% | 64.4% | Idea 2 |\n   180→| Per-step MAPE (no KV) | 83.8% | 43.9% | Idea 2 |\n   181→| BLIS E2E mean error | Not tested | 427.8% | — |\n   182→| ITL mean error | Not tested | 33.6% (5/10 <10%) | Idea 2 |\n   183→| LOMO avg MAPE | 148.8% | 108.6% | Idea 2 |\n   184→| LOWO avg MAPE | 155.4% | 117.4% | Idea 2 |\n   185→| KV feature contribution | -3.6pp (harmful) | -20.5pp (harmful) | Neither |\n   186→\n   187→**Idea 2 is strictly better but both fail all primary targets.** The 3-regime structure, overhead floor, and BLIS integration pipeline from Idea 2 are the foundation to build on.\n   188→\n   189→---\n   190→\n   191→## 7. Per-Experiment Leaderboard (BLIS E2E)\n   192→\n   193→Best results achieved in Round 2 (Idea 2 with regime Ridge + overhead floor):\n   194→\n   195→| Experiment | E2E Error | TTFT Error | ITL Error | Baseline E2E |\n   196→|---|---|---|---|---|\n   197→| 34b-roleplay | **3.3%** | 282.7% | 100.1% | 136.5% |\n   198→| mixtral-roleplay | 50.8% | 77.2% | **0.7%** | 141.9% |\n   199→| mixtral-codegen | 51.5% | 76.5% | **2.1%** | 141.3% |\n   200→| 7b-roleplay | 52.5% | 78.4% | **4.0%** | 86.1% |\n   201→| 70b-hf-codegen | 55.7% | 77.7% | 10.7% | — |\n   202→| 70b-roleplay | 55.6% | 77.9% | 10.3% | — |\n   203→| mixtral-general | 554.6% | 44,464% | **8.7%** | 138.5% |\n   204→| 70b-general | 182.7% | 12,567% | 23.5% | 111.8% |\n   205→| 34b-codegen | 370.2% | 30,425% | 95.9% | 135.4% |\n   206→| 34b-general | 2,901.1% | 230,931% | 80.3% | 132.3% |\n   207→\n   208→**Observations:**\n   209→- Only 1/10 experiments meets <10% E2E target (34b-roleplay, likely coincidental)\n   210→- TTFT errors are the dominant E2E contributor — they're 2-3 orders of magnitude worse than ITL\n   211→- ITL is well-solved for 7B, Mixtral, and partially for 70B\n   212→- CodeLlama-34B \"general\" is catastrophic across all metrics\n   213→\n   214→---\n   215→\n   216→## 8. Binding Constraints for Round 3\n   217→\n   218→### 8.1 TTFT/Workload Spec Mismatch (PRIMARY — Blocking E2E Target)\n   219→\n   220→The 31,906% mean TTFT error is the single biggest obstacle to <10% E2E. This is NOT a step-time problem — it's a simulation-fidelity problem in how BLIS generates and schedules requests compared to the real system. Until TTFT is addressed, no step-time improvement can achieve the E2E target.\n   221→\n   222→**Actionable:** Diagnose whether the workload spec generator, BLIS request injection timing, or BLIS prefill scheduling is the root cause. Compare BLIS-simulated request arrival/scheduling timestamps against ground-truth lifecycle data.\n   223→\n   224→### 8.2 KV Feature Scaling (SECONDARY — Blocking Per-Step Improvement)\n   225→\n   226→Per-request KV features (the key Round 1 recommendation) hurt accuracy due to numerical instability in raw linear space. The features themselves are not wrong — the regression formulation is.\n   227→\n   228→**Actionable:** Apply StandardScaler within the Ridge pipeline, or use log-transformed features (not target), or switch to a model that handles large feature ranges (tree ensemble, or feature-scaled Ridge).\n   229→\n   230→### 8.3 CodeLlama-34B Anomaly (SECONDARY)\n   231→\n   232→34B is the worst model by a wide margin across all metrics. The specific batch dynamics causing this need investigation (batch-size distributions, step-time outliers, prefill/decode ratios).\n   233→\n   234→**Actionable:** Profile 34B's step-time distribution, batch-size histogram, and KV utilization compared to other models. Determine if it's a data quality issue, architecture anomaly, or model-specific coefficient problem.\n   235→\n   236→### 8.4 Mixed-Heavy Regime Sparsity (TERTIARY)\n   237→\n   238→The 3-regime design collapses to 2 effective regimes because only 0.1% of steps are mixed-heavy. This regime needs more data (perhaps from reasoning workloads, which were excluded from Round 2 data) or the threshold needs lowering.\n   239→\n   240→---\n   241→\n   242→## 9. Successful Techniques to Preserve\n   243→\n   244→1. **Overhead floor (`max(overhead, compute)`)** — the most impactful single technique\n   245→2. **Per-model training** — mandatory due to 3+ OOM step-time variation\n   246→3. **Regime separation** (decode-only vs mixed) — provides distinct modeling contexts\n   247→4. **Temporal train/test split** — prevents autocorrelation leakage\n   248→5. **BLIS E2E validation pipeline** (Idea 2's `validate_e2e.py` + `validate_blis.py`) — the infrastructure for running BLIS with custom coefficients and comparing against ground truth\n   249→6. **Per-model overhead derivation** from ground-truth ITL\n   250→7. **Secondary method constant extraction** from lifecycle data (even though they contributed 0pp, the extraction pipeline is correct)\n   251→\n   252→---\n   253→\n   254→## 10. Eliminated Approaches (Do Not Repeat)\n   255→\n   256→| Approach | Why It Failed | Round |\n   257→|---|---|---|\n   258→| Global models (all experiments) | 3+ OOM step-time scale variation | R1 |\n   259→| Analytical FLOPs decomposition without per-request KV | decode_attention = 0, structurally incomplete | R1 |\n   260→| Correction factors on incomplete backbone | Pathological compensation (factor=39.5 on zero signal) | R1 |\n   261→| Pure-phase analysis | Only 6 pure-prefill steps exist under chunked prefill | R1 |\n   262→| **Raw KV features in linear regression** | kv_sum up to 64K causes Ridge coefficient instability | R2 |\n   263→| **2-regime piecewise linear** | Too coarse — mixed-batch heterogeneity too high for one linear regime | R2 |\n   264→| **Joint Bayesian optimization** | Cannot compensate for structural model errors | R2 |\n   265→| **Secondary method calibration alone** | 200-400us corrections invisible against 100%+ E2E errors | R2 |\n   266→| **Log-space target with large features** | expm1 causes exponential blowup with KV/prefill coefficients | R2 |\n   267→\n   268→---\n   269→\n   270→## 11. Summary for Future Ideation\n   271→\n   272→### What the data tells us after 2 rounds:\n   273→\n   274→1. **The overhead floor is the workhorse** — ITL is solved for 4/5 models without any sophisticated step-time model\n   275→2. **TTFT errors dominate E2E** — the step-time model is nearly irrelevant to E2E accuracy until TTFT is fixed\n   276→3. **KV features have signal but need proper scaling** — they're counter-productive in raw linear space, productive when the model handles their dynamic range\n   277→4. **Per-model calibration is non-negotiable** — step-time scales vary 3+ orders of magnitude\n   278→5. **The 3-regime + overhead floor architecture is sound** — it just needs (a) TTFT fix, (b) feature scaling, (c) 34B investigation\n   279→\n   280→### What Round 3 should prioritize (ordered):\n   281→\n   282→1. **Diagnose and fix the TTFT mismatch** — this is the gating issue for E2E. Without it, no step-time improvement matters.\n   283→2. **Apply feature scaling to KV features** — StandardScaler, log-transform, or tree models. The features themselves are available and meaningful; only the regression formulation is wrong.\n   284→3. **Investigate CodeLlama-34B** — determine if the anomaly is data, architecture, or coefficients.\n   285→4. **Lower mixed-heavy threshold or add reasoning data** — the 256-token boundary sees only 74 steps. Consider 64 or 128 tokens, or include reasoning workloads.\n   286→\n   287→### Hard constraints to respect:\n   288→- Per-model training mandatory (LOMO still >80%)\n   289→- Features must be computable from `[]*Request` with `ProgressIndex` (Go integration)\n   290→- Prediction latency <1ms per step\n   291→- Pure-Go implementation (no Python/ONNX runtime)\n   292→\n   293→---\n   294→\n   295→## 12. Cumulative Round History\n   296→\n   297→| Round | Best E2E Error | Best ITL Error | Key Achievement | Primary Blocker |\n   298→|---|---|---|---|---|\n   299→| R1 | Not tested (Python-only) | Not tested | 34% per-step MAPE with XGBoost (2x better than blackbox) | No BLIS integration, no E2E validation |\n   300→| **R2** | **427.8% mean** (1/10 <10%) | **33.6% mean** (5/10 <10%) | Overhead floor + BLIS pipeline + per-request KV features | **TTFT mismatch (31,906%)** dominates E2E; KV features counter-productive in linear space |\n   301→\n   302→---\n   303→\n   304→## 13. Reproducibility\n   305→\n   306→All code is in `hypotheses/h-stepml/round2/`:\n   307→\n   308→```\n   309→round2/\n   310→├── FINDINGS_ROUND2.md              # This file\n   311→├── idea-1-bayesian-calibration/\n   312→│   ├── FINDINGS_SUMMARY.md\n   313→│   ├── h1-piecewise-steptime/      # 2-regime Ridge (run.sh, train_piecewise.py)\n   314→│   ├── h2-joint-bo-calibration/    # Blocked (bo_calibrate.py ready but not run)\n   315→│   ├── h4-model-generalization/    # LOMO (lomo_cv.py)\n   316→│   └── h5-workload-generalization/ # LOWO (lowo_cv.py)\n   317→└── idea-2-regime-ensemble/\n   318→    ├── FINDINGS_SUMMARY.md\n   319→    ├── h1-kv-regime-models/        # 3-regime Ridge (train_regime_ridge.py)\n   320→    ├── h2-blis-e2e-validation/     # BLIS E2E (validate_e2e.py)\n   321→    ├── h3-secondary-method-calibration/ # Ablation (calibrate_secondary.py)\n   322→    ├── h4-model-generalization/    # LOMO (lomo_cv.py)\n   323→    └── h5-workload-generalization/ # LOWO (lowo_cv.py)\n   324→```\n   325→\n   326→**Dependencies:** Python 3, pandas, scikit-learn, scipy, numpy\n   327→**Data:** `eval/ground_truth/` (77,816 steps from 10 experiments)\n   328→**BLIS integration:** `sim/latency/stepml.go` (Go StepTime with floor/cap logic)\n   329→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Vx9FActZvVu6PzWLHbXEX2","session_id":"7ea608f4-4aa5-4264-9119-cf38f8fb2f5c","uuid":"ac358903-ad74-468c-b21f-5d25154c5c7f"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01PL4YjVCQqUEfWKBjkME2CW","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# StepML Round 1: Findings Summary\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-02-26\n     4→**Branch:** `stepml-experiments`\n     5→**Purpose:** Comprehensive summary of all Round 1 experiments to inform future rounds of ideation and testing.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## 1. Problem Recap\n    10→\n    11→Replace BLIS's 3-coefficient blackbox latency model (`step_time = beta0 + beta1*prefill_tokens + beta2*decode_tokens`) with a data-driven predictor achieving **<10% workload-level E2E mean error** across 16 experiments (4 models × 4 workloads, H100 GPUs). The winning model must integrate into BLIS as a Go `LatencyModel` implementation.\n    12→\n    13→**Data:** 122,752 step-level observations from instrumented vLLM v0.15.1 with OpenTelemetry tracing (10% sample rate).\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→## 2. What We Tried\n    18→\n    19→### Idea 1: Physics-Informed Tree Ensemble\n    20→\n    21→**Approach:** Engineer 30 physics-informed features from batch composition and architecture parameters, train XGBoost per-experiment.\n    22→\n    23→| Sub-Hypothesis | Result | Key Number |\n    24→|---|---|---|\n    25→| h1: 30 features + Ridge | Weakly Supported (per-exp) | 92.1% avg MAPE per-exp; global 301.7% short-circuited |\n    26→| h2: XGBoost per-experiment | **Weakly Supported** | **34.0% avg MAPE** (2x better than blackbox 70.4%) |\n    27→| h3: Cross-config generalization | Not Supported | LOMO 2559.7%, LOWO 109.7% |\n    28→\n    29→### Idea 2: Analytical Decomposition + Learned Corrections\n    30→\n    31→**Approach:** Decompose step time into 4 analytical FLOPs components (prefill GEMM, prefill attention, decode GEMM, decode attention), then learn multiplicative correction factors.\n    32→\n    33→| Sub-Hypothesis | Result | Key Number |\n    34→|---|---|---|\n    35→| h1: Component correlation | Not Supported | 0/4 components > 0.8 Pearson r |\n    36→| h2: Correction factors | Not Supported | 78.7% avg MAPE (worse than blackbox 70.4%) |\n    37→\n    38→### Idea 3: Evolutionary Synthesis (OpenEvolve)\n    39→\n    40→**Status:** Deferred — h2 depends on Idea 2's analytical components (which are structurally incomplete), and OpenEvolve infrastructure was not set up.\n    41→\n    42→---\n    43→\n    44→## 3. What Worked\n    45→\n    46→### 3.1 Per-Experiment XGBoost (Best Result)\n    47→\n    48→XGBoost with 30 physics-informed features, trained separately per experiment:\n    49→- **Average MAPE: 34.0%** (vs blackbox 70.4%) — **2x improvement**\n    50→- **5/16 experiments < 15% MAPE**, 9/16 < 30%\n    51→- **Zero regressions** — beats or matches blackbox on all 16 experiments\n    52→- Biggest wins: reasoning workloads (Llama-7B-reasoning: 123.5% → 13.0%, Mixtral-reasoning: 222.8% → 62.4%)\n    53→\n    54→**Full per-experiment leaderboard (XGBoost vs Blackbox):**\n    55→\n    56→| Model | Workload | XGB MAPE | BB MAPE | Improvement |\n    57→|-------|----------|----------|---------|-------------|\n    58→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | general | 9.1% | 9.2% | +0.1 pp |\n    59→| llama-2-70b-hf | reasoning | 9.8% | 14.2% | +4.4 pp |\n    60→| llama-2-7b | reasoning | 13.0% | 123.5% | +110.5 pp |\n    61→| codellama-34b | reasoning | 14.0% | 37.3% | +23.3 pp |\n    62→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | codegen | 14.7% | 19.0% | +4.3 pp |\n    63→| codellama-34b | codegen | 16.1% | 21.6% | +5.5 pp |\n    64→| codellama-34b | roleplay | 25.7% | 30.8% | +5.1 pp |\n    65→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | roleplay | 28.3% | 33.6% | +5.3 pp |\n    66→| llama-2-70b | roleplay | 28.3% | 128.6% | +100.2 pp |\n    67→| llama-2-7b | roleplay | 30.9% | 40.3% | +9.4 pp |\n    68→| llama-2-70b-hf | codegen | 31.1% | 90.8% | +59.7 pp |\n    69→| llama-2-7b | codegen | 33.4% | 69.7% | +36.3 pp |\n    70→| llama-2-7b | general | 50.9% | 72.9% | +22.0 pp |\n    71→| llama-2-70b | general | 55.4% | 61.2% | +5.7 pp |\n    72→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | reasoning | 62.4% | 222.8% | +160.5 pp |\n    73→| codellama-34b | general | 121.5% | 151.1% | +29.6 pp |\n    74→\n    75→### 3.2 Feature Engineering Insights\n    76→\n    77→The 30 features in 6 groups provided clear value over the 2-feature blackbox. Most informative features by XGBoost importance:\n    78→\n    79→| Rank | Feature | Description | Why It Helps |\n    80→|------|---------|-------------|-------------|\n    81→| 1 | `f_kv_blocks_used` | GPU KV cache blocks occupied | Best available proxy for total context length across all running requests |\n    82→| 2 | `f_decode_tokens` | Decode tokens in batch | Core batch computation feature (already in blackbox) |\n    83→| 3 | `f_running_depth` | Number of running requests | Proxy for batch complexity and attention fan-out |\n    84→| 4 | `f_prefill_tokens` | Prefill tokens in batch | Core batch computation feature (already in blackbox) |\n    85→| 5 | `f_num_decode_reqs` | Decode request count | Captures batch shape vs just token count |\n    86→| 6 | `f_total_flops_estimate` | Analytical FLOPs estimate | Physics-informed feature — strong for Mixtral |\n    87→| 7 | `f_prefill_x_decode` | Interaction: prefill × decode | Captures non-additive mixed-batch overhead |\n    88→| 8 | `f_decode_memory_intensity` | Memory bytes / decode FLOPs | Compute vs memory bound indicator |\n    89→| 9 | `f_batch_size_x_kv_pressure` | Interaction: batch_size × kv_max | Attention memory pressure |\n    90→| 10 | `f_kv_blocks_free` | Free GPU KV cache blocks | Inverse proxy for system load |\n    91→\n    92→**Key observation:** The top features are dominated by **KV cache state proxies** (`kv_blocks_used`, `running_depth`, `kv_blocks_free`) rather than physics features. The model is learning to predict step time from system state because per-request KV information is missing.\n    93→\n    94→### 3.3 Analytical Decomposition Has Signal Where GEMM Dominates\n    95→\n    96→Per-experiment correlation of total analytical FLOPs estimate with step duration:\n    97→\n    98→| Correlation Range | Workload Type | Example |\n    99→|---|---|---|\n   100→| r > 0.85 | General (GEMM-dominated) | Mixtral-general r=0.94, Llama-7B-general r=0.86 |\n   101→| r = 0.35–0.65 | Codegen (mixed) | CodeLlama-codegen r=0.43 |\n   102→| r < 0.25 | Reasoning/roleplay (attention-dominated) | Mixtral-reasoning r=0.02, Llama-7B-reasoning r=0.12 |\n   103→\n   104→The physics is correct where GEMM dominates — but attention cost (which depends on per-request KV lengths) is the dominant component for reasoning/roleplay workloads.\n   105→\n   106→---\n   107→\n   108→## 4. What Failed and Why\n   109→\n   110→### 4.1 Global Models (Catastrophic Failure)\n   111→\n   112→Any model trained across all 16 experiments fails catastrophically:\n   113→- **Global Ridge 30f:** 301.7% MAPE\n   114→- **Global blackbox:** 670% MAPE\n   115→\n   116→**Root cause:** Step times span 3+ orders of magnitude across model configurations:\n   117→- Llama-2-7B (tp=1): 12–500 μs per step\n   118→- Llama-2-70B (tp=4): 500–250,000 μs per step\n   119→\n   120→A single model cannot fit both scales. Per-experiment (or per-model) training is mandatory.\n   121→\n   122→### 4.2 Cross-Model Generalization (Structural Failure)\n   123→\n   124→LOMO (Leave-One-Model-Out) XGBoost:\n   125→\n   126→| Holdout Model | Test MAPE | Why |\n   127→|---|---|---|\n   128→| llama-2-7b | **9908%** | tp=1 model with μs-scale steps; trained on tp=2/4 models with ms-scale steps |\n   129→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | 186.6% | MoE architecture fundamentally different from dense training models |\n   130→| codellama-34b | 78.9% | Less extreme but still 5x worse than per-experiment |\n   131→| llama-2-70b | 65.5% | Closest to training distribution (similar scale) |\n   132→\n   133→**Root cause:** Features encode absolute values (FLOPs, KV blocks) that scale with model size. Architecture metadata (`model_id`, `tp_degree`, `is_moe`) is insufficient to bridge the scale gap. This is **not a model capacity issue** — it's a representation issue.\n   134→\n   135→### 4.3 Cross-Workload Generalization (Moderate Failure)\n   136→\n   137→LOWO (Leave-One-Workload-Out) XGBoost:\n   138→\n   139→| Holdout Workload | Test MAPE | Why |\n   140→|---|---|---|\n   141→| roleplay | 30.6% | Similar batch patterns to codegen — some transfer |\n   142→| codegen | 53.4% | Moderate transfer from other workloads |\n   143→| reasoning | 53.2% | Long contexts not well represented in other workloads |\n   144→| general | **301.6%** | Most diverse batch compositions — unpredictable from other workloads |\n   145→\n   146→**Root cause:** Less severe than LOMO because same model config → same step time scale. Failures concentrate in \"general\" workloads (most diverse batch compositions) and \"reasoning\" (long contexts with extreme KV lengths).\n   147→\n   148→### 4.4 Analytical Decomposition (Structural Incompleteness)\n   149→\n   150→The 4-component FLOPs decomposition fails because:\n   151→\n   152→1. **decode_attention_flops = 0** for all steps. Per-request KV cache lengths (`ProgressIndex`) are unavailable in step-level data. Decode attention is the dominant cost for 80.6% of steps (pure decode), making the decomposition structurally incomplete.\n   153→\n   154→2. **Only 6 pure-prefill steps** exist (out of 122,752). vLLM's chunked prefill makes nearly every batch mixed. The experimental design assumed large pure-phase subsets for correlation analysis — this assumption was wrong.\n   155→\n   156→3. **Correction factors compensate pathologically:** The optimizer set `decode_attn_factor = 39.5` trying to amplify a zero signal. The 36-parameter model (78.7% MAPE) actually performed **worse than the 3-parameter blackbox** (70.4%) because the analytical backbone with missing attention is less informative than raw `decode_tokens`.\n   157→\n   158→### 4.5 \"General\" Workloads Are Consistently Hardest\n   159→\n   160→Across all models and approaches, the 4 \"general\" workload experiments are the worst:\n   161→\n   162→| Model | General MAPE (XGB) | Next-Worst MAPE (XGB) |\n   163→|-------|--------------------|-----------------------|\n   164→| codellama-34b | **121.5%** | 25.7% (roleplay) |\n   165→| llama-2-70b | **55.4%** | 28.3% (roleplay) |\n   166→| llama-2-7b | **50.9%** | 30.9% (roleplay) |\n   167→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | 9.1% (exception — Mixtral-general is easy) | 28.3% (roleplay) |\n   168→\n   169→**Root cause:** \"General\" workloads have the most diverse batch compositions — mixing short decode-only batches with occasional large prefill+decode batches. High step time variance within a single experiment makes prediction difficult even with 30 features.\n   170→\n   171→---\n   172→\n   173→## 5. Binding Constraints (What Blocks Further Progress)\n   174→\n   175→### 5.1 Missing Per-Request KV Cache Lengths (PRIMARY)\n   176→\n   177→The single most impactful limitation. The step-level training data contains only aggregate batch features (`batch.prefill_tokens`, `batch.decode_tokens`), not per-request KV cache lengths.\n   178→\n   179→**Impact on each approach:**\n   180→- **XGBoost:** Uses system-state proxies (`kv_blocks_used`, `running_depth`) instead of per-request statistics (`kv_mean`, `kv_max`, `kv_sum`). These proxies capture occupancy but not per-request distribution. Two batches with identical total KV blocks but different per-request distributions (many short vs few long) have very different attention costs.\n   181→- **Analytical decomposition:** Decode attention FLOPs are literally uncomputable. This makes the decomposition incomplete for the dominant cost component.\n   182→- **Feature importance confirms it:** XGBoost's top features are all KV state proxies — the model is begging for better KV information.\n   183→\n   184→**Available in simulator:** BLIS's `LatencyModel.StepTime()` receives `[]*Request`, each with `ProgressIndex` (cumulative input_processed + output_generated). This is the per-request KV cache length proxy. It's available at prediction time but was NOT available in the training data.\n   185→\n   186→**Possible solutions for Round 2:**\n   187→1. Re-instrument vLLM to export per-request KV lengths in step-level traces\n   188→2. Derive approximate per-request KV lengths from per-request lifecycle data (already available in `request_metrics/`)\n   189→3. Design features that work without per-request KV (the approach we took, but with a ceiling)\n   190→\n   191→### 5.2 Step Time Scale Variation (SECONDARY)\n   192→\n   193→3+ orders of magnitude across model configurations. Forces per-model training. Not addressable without normalized/relative features.\n   194→\n   195→**Possible solutions for Round 2:**\n   196→1. **Log-scale prediction:** Predict `log(step_time)` instead of `step_time` — compresses the range\n   197→2. **Normalized features:** Divide FLOPs by model-specific capacity (peak_flops × tp_degree) to produce utilization features that are scale-independent\n   198→3. **Relative prediction:** Predict `step_time / baseline_step_time` where baseline is a reference batch configuration\n   199→4. **Hierarchical models:** Model-specific first stage (captures scale) + shared second stage (captures batch composition effects)\n   200→\n   201→### 5.3 Hyperparameter Underfitting (TERTIARY)\n   202→\n   203→XGBoost consistently selected shallow trees (max_depth=4, n_estimators=100) for 13/16 experiments. This suggests the model is **underfitting, not overfitting** — more expressive features would help more than deeper trees. The feature set, not the model capacity, is the bottleneck.\n   204→\n   205→---\n   206→\n   207→## 6. Data Characteristics Learned\n   208→\n   209→### 6.1 Phase Distribution\n   210→\n   211→| Phase | Steps | % of Total |\n   212→|-------|-------|-----------|\n   213→| Pure decode (prefill_tokens = 0) | 98,961 | 80.6% |\n   214→| Mixed batch (prefill + decode) | 23,789 | 19.4% |\n   215→| Pure prefill (decode_tokens = 0) | 6 | 0.005% |\n   216→\n   217→**Implication:** vLLM's chunked prefill makes nearly every batch mixed or pure-decode. Experimental designs assuming large pure-prefill subsets (like Idea 2) are invalid. Any step-time model must primarily handle decode-dominated and mixed batches.\n   218→\n   219→### 6.2 Step Time Distribution by Workload Type\n   220→\n   221→| Workload | Mean Duration | Median Duration | Std Dev | Coefficient of Variation |\n   222→|----------|--------------|-----------------|---------|------------------------|\n   223→| reasoning | 6,000–33,500 μs | High variance | Very high | >1.0 (bimodal) |\n   224→| general | 200–2,000 μs | Moderate | High | >0.8 |\n   225→| codegen | 160–320 μs | Low | Low-moderate | 0.3–0.6 |\n   226→| roleplay | 160–320 μs | Low | Low-moderate | 0.3–0.6 |\n   227→\n   228→**Implication:** Reasoning workloads have extremely high variance and bimodal distributions (long prefills interspersed with short decodes). This drives high MAPE even for models that capture the mean well.\n   229→\n   230→### 6.3 Feature Correlation Structure\n   231→\n   232→- `batch.prefill_tokens` and `batch.decode_tokens` are weakly correlated (r ≈ 0.1–0.3) — they provide mostly independent information\n   233→- `kv_blocks_used` and `running_depth` are moderately correlated (r ≈ 0.4–0.7) — both capture system load\n   234→- Physics features (`total_flops_estimate`, `arithmetic_intensity`) are highly correlated with `prefill_tokens` on prefill-heavy workloads but nearly orthogonal on decode-heavy workloads\n   235→- Interaction terms (`prefill_x_decode`, `batch_size_x_kv_pressure`) add unique variance that individual features don't capture\n   236→\n   237→### 6.4 Experiments Per Model\n   238→\n   239→| Model | TP | Steps | Avg Step Time | Experiments |\n   240→|-------|-----|-------|---------------|-------------|\n   241→| llama-2-7b | 1 | 47,034 | ~160–5,000 μs | 4 |\n   242→| llama-2-70b / 70b-hf | 4 | 23,860 | ~500–33,500 μs | 4 |\n   243→| codellama-34b | 2 | 29,094 | ~200–6,000 μs | 4 |\n   244→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | 2 | 22,764 | ~160–8,000 μs | 4 |\n   245→\n   246→**Implication:** Llama-7B has the most steps (47K) — heavily represented. Data is not balanced across models.\n   247→\n   248→---\n   249→\n   250→## 7. Successful Techniques and Patterns\n   251→\n   252→### 7.1 Temporal Train/Test Split\n   253→\n   254→The 60/20/20 temporal split (earlier steps for training, later for testing) prevents autocorrelation leakage. This is critical because consecutive steps share system state (KV cache occupancy, queue depth) which could inflate accuracy artificially.\n   255→\n   256→### 7.2 Per-Experiment Training\n   257→\n   258→The only viable approach — step time scale varies 3+ orders of magnitude across model configurations. All production inference simulators (Vidur, Splitwise) use per-model calibration.\n   259→\n   260→### 7.3 System-State KV Proxies\n   261→\n   262→While imperfect, `kv_blocks_used`, `kv_blocks_free`, and `running_depth` provide meaningful signal about KV cache pressure. They correlate with step time because they capture total context length indirectly. However, they cannot distinguish per-request KV distribution.\n   263→\n   264→### 7.4 Physics-Informed Interaction Terms\n   265→\n   266→`prefill_x_decode` (prefill_tokens × decode_tokens) and `batch_size_x_kv_pressure` (batch_size × kv_max) capture non-additive mixed-batch effects that individual features miss. These were among the top 10 features for several experiments.\n   267→\n   268→---\n   269→\n   270→## 8. Failed Techniques and Anti-Patterns\n   271→\n   272→### 8.1 Global Models\n   273→\n   274→Any model trained across all experiments fails catastrophically due to step time scale variation. Do not attempt global training without scale normalization.\n   275→\n   276→### 8.2 Analytical Decomposition Without Per-Request KV\n   277→\n   278→The 4-component FLOPs decomposition is physically correct but computationally incomplete without per-request KV lengths. The `decode_attention = 0` problem makes the decomposition worse than the simple blackbox.\n   279→\n   280→### 8.3 Correction Factors on Incomplete Backbone\n   281→\n   282→Learned multiplicative corrections cannot fix a structurally incomplete model. The optimizer compensates pathologically (factor=39.5 on zero signal). If the backbone is missing a component, add the component — don't amplify the existing ones.\n   283→\n   284→### 8.4 Pure-Phase Analysis with Chunked Prefill\n   285→\n   286→vLLM's chunked prefill produces only 6 pure-prefill steps. Experimental designs relying on pure-phase subsets are invalid under continuous batching with chunked prefill.\n   287→\n   288→---\n   289→\n   290→## 9. Round 1 Design Limitations\n   291→\n   292→Round 1 focused narrowly on **per-step time prediction in isolation**. Several aspects of the full BLIS latency pipeline were explicitly out of scope, limiting both the validity and applicability of results.\n   293→\n   294→### 9.1 Step-Time-Only Modeling\n   295→\n   296→All Round 1 experiments predicted raw step duration (`step_time_us`) without modeling the full request lifecycle. In BLIS, observed latency includes:\n   297→- **Queueing delay**: Time spent in WaitQ before scheduling (driven by `AlphaCoeffs`)\n   298→- **Scheduling overhead**: Batch formation decisions, preemption logic\n   299→- **KV cache events**: Allocation latency, eviction/reload cycles (GPU↔CPU offload), transfer delays\n   300→- **Inter-step gaps**: Time between consecutive steps (event loop overhead, snapshot refresh)\n   301→\n   302→Round 1 treated step time as the entire signal. In practice, queueing and KV events can dominate E2E latency under load — a model that perfectly predicts step time but ignores these components would still produce large E2E errors.\n   303→\n   304→### 9.2 No BLIS (Go) Integration or Validation\n   305→\n   306→All experiments ran in Python (scikit-learn, XGBoost, scipy). No model was integrated into BLIS's Go `LatencyModel` interface, and no E2E simulation validation was performed. This means:\n   307→- The 34% per-step MAPE was never validated against workload-level E2E metrics (TTFT, TPOT, throughput)\n   308→- Error cancellation effects (symmetric per-step errors averaging out over a request's lifetime) were not measured\n   309→- Interaction between step-time prediction errors and scheduling/routing decisions was not tested\n   310→- Feasibility of pure-Go implementation (no Python/ONNX runtime) was not demonstrated\n   311→\n   312→### 9.2.1 Weaker Per-Experiment Baseline\n   313→\n   314→Round 1's blackbox baseline was fitted **per experiment** (16 separate regressions — one per model×workload combination). This is an artificially easy bar to beat: in production, you calibrate once per model deployment, not once per workload type.\n   315→\n   316→A stronger baseline fits one linear regression **per model+TP**, pooling all workloads for that model into a single training set. This forces the 3 coefficients `(beta0, beta1, beta2)` to generalize across general, codegen, roleplay, and reasoning workloads simultaneously — a harder regression problem that better reflects real deployment conditions.\n   317→\n   318→Round 1's claimed \"2x improvement\" (34% XGBoost vs 70.4% blackbox) was measured against the weaker per-experiment baseline. The improvement margin against a per-model pooled baseline — which must also be validated through BLIS E2E simulation, not just per-step MAPE — may differ substantially.\n   319→\n   320→### 9.3 No Scheduling or Queueing Delay Modeling\n   321→\n   322→BLIS's `LatencyModel` interface has 5 methods, not just `StepTime()`:\n   323→- `QueueDelayEstimate()` — estimated wait before first scheduling\n   324→- `PreemptionCost()` — cost of evicting/reloading KV blocks\n   325→- `StepTime()` — per-step compute duration (**the only method Round 1 modeled**)\n   326→- `PrefillChunkSize()` — chunked prefill granularity\n   327→- `IsMemoryBound()` — compute vs memory bound indicator\n   328→\n   329→Round 1 only addressed `StepTime()`. The other methods use separate coefficient families (`AlphaCoeffs`) or analytical estimates that were not studied. A complete `LatencyModel` replacement requires data-driven approaches for all five methods.\n   330→\n   331→### 9.4 KV Cache Dynamics Ignored\n   332→\n   333→Step-time prediction was treated as a stateless function of batch composition. In reality:\n   334→- KV block allocation/deallocation affects available GPU memory and can trigger eviction\n   335→- Tiered KV (GPU+CPU) introduces transfer latencies that add to effective step time\n   336→- Preemption decisions depend on KV pressure, creating feedback loops between step time and system state\n   337→\n   338→Round 1's training data captured KV block counts as static features but did not model the dynamic KV lifecycle or its impact on step timing.\n   339→\n   340→### 9.5 Offline Python Analysis vs Online Go Prediction\n   341→\n   342→Round 1 used offline batch prediction (train on historical traces, evaluate on held-out test set). BLIS requires online prediction — `StepTime()` is called on every scheduler iteration with the current batch composition. This creates constraints Round 1 did not address:\n   343→- **Prediction latency**: Must be <1ms per call (XGBoost inference overhead in pure Go unknown)\n   344→- **Feature availability**: Some features used in Round 1 (e.g., `kv_blocks_free`, `running_depth`) are available differently in the simulator vs in training data\n   345→- **Statefulness**: The simulator calls `StepTime()` with `[]*Request` (each carrying `ProgressIndex`), not with pre-computed aggregate features — the feature engineering must happen inside the Go method\n   346→\n   347→---\n   348→\n   349→## 10. Open Questions for Round 2\n   350→\n   351→### 10.1 Can Per-Request KV Features Close the Gap?\n   352→\n   353→The `ProgressIndex` field is available per-request in the BLIS simulator. If we can either:\n   354→- (a) Derive per-request KV lengths from the per-request lifecycle data in `eval/ground_truth/*/request_metrics/`, or\n   355→- (b) Extend the training data to include per-request KV lengths\n   356→\n   357→...then both XGBoost and the analytical decomposition should improve substantially. The feature importance analysis shows the model is bottlenecked by KV information quality.\n   358→\n   359→### 10.2 Can Log-Scale or Normalized Prediction Enable Cross-Model Models?\n   360→\n   361→Per-model training works but requires N separate calibration runs. If features were normalized to model-specific capacity (e.g., FLOPs / peak_throughput, step_time / reference_step_time), a single model might generalize across configurations.\n   362→\n   363→### 10.3 Is Per-Step MAPE the Right Diagnostic?\n   364→\n   365→The primary metric is workload-level E2E mean error (not per-step MAPE). Per-step errors may cancel in aggregate. The 34% per-step MAPE might translate to <10% E2E mean error if errors are symmetric. This was NOT tested in Round 1. Round 2 should include BLIS E2E validation.\n   366→\n   367→### 10.4 Would More Training Data Help?\n   368→\n   369→Current per-experiment training sizes are 2,000–9,000 steps. The consistently shallow XGBoost trees suggest underfitting due to insufficient features, not insufficient data. But more diverse batch compositions (especially for \"general\" workloads) might help.\n   370→\n   371→### 10.5 Can We Leverage the Per-Request Lifecycle Data?\n   372→\n   373→The `eval/ground_truth/*/request_metrics/` directories contain per-token timestamps, input/output token counts, and E2E latencies. This data could:\n   374→- Derive approximate per-request KV lengths (ProgressIndex at each step)\n   375→- Enable workload-level E2E validation (compare predicted vs observed per-request E2E)\n   376→- Provide TTFT/ITL breakdown for Priority 2 metrics\n   377→\n   378→### 10.6 What About Simpler Models with Better Features?\n   379→\n   380→XGBoost with 30 features beats Ridge with 30 features by 2.7x (34% vs 92% avg MAPE). But the 30 features include several that are imprecise (KV proxies) or constant (attention ratios set to 0/1). A smaller set of high-quality features might enable simpler models (e.g., Ridge or piecewise linear) that are easier to integrate in Go.\n   381→\n   382→### 10.7 Can We Handle \"General\" Workloads Better?\n   383→\n   384→The 4 \"general\" experiments are consistently the hardest (50–121% MAPE for XGBoost). These have the most diverse batch compositions. Potential approaches:\n   385→- Cluster steps by batch composition type, train separate models per cluster\n   386→- Add batch composition entropy/diversity features\n   387→- Use quantile regression to handle bimodal step time distributions\n   388→\n   389→### 10.8 Idea 3 Feasibility Without Idea 2\n   390→\n   391→Evolutionary synthesis (OpenEvolve) was deferred because h2 depends on Idea 2's components. But h1 (evolving raw feature combinations) has no dependency on Idea 2 and could still discover non-obvious feature interactions. Worth revisiting if OpenEvolve infrastructure becomes available.\n   392→\n   393→---\n   394→\n   395→## 11. Reproducibility\n   396→\n   397→All experiment code is in `hypotheses/h-stepml/`:\n   398→\n   399→```\n   400→hypotheses/h-stepml/\n   401→├── shared/                      # Infrastructure (data_loader, splits, evaluation)\n   402→├── idea-1-tree-ensemble/\n   403→│   ├── h1-features/             # 30-feature Ridge regression\n   404→│   │   ├── run.sh               # Orchestrator\n   405→│   │   ├── engineer_features.py # Feature engineering (30 features, 6 groups)\n   406→│   │   ├── train_ridge.py       # Ridge training + prediction\n   407→│   │   ├── analyze.py           # Evaluation against baselines\n   408→│   │   └── FINDINGS.md          # Results and analysis\n   409→│   ├── h2-model/                # XGBoost per-experiment\n   410→│   │   ├── run.sh\n   411→│   │   ├── train_xgboost.py     # XGBoost grid search + training\n   412→│   │   ├── analyze.py\n   413→│   │   └── FINDINGS.md\n   414→│   └── h3-generalization/       # LOMO + LOWO cross-validation\n   415→│       ├── run.sh\n   416→│       ├── cross_validate.py    # Leave-one-out cross-validation\n   417→│       ├── analyze.py\n   418→│       └── FINDINGS.md\n   419→├── idea-2-analytical-decomposition/\n   420→│   ├── h1-features/             # 4-component FLOPs decomposition\n   421→│   │   ├── run.sh\n   422→│   │   ├── compute_components.py # Analytical FLOPs computation\n   423→│   │   ├── analyze.py\n   424→│   │   └── FINDINGS.md\n   425→│   └── h2-model/                # Learned correction factors\n   426→│       ├── run.sh\n   427→│       ├── fit_corrections.py   # Nonlinear least squares fitting\n   428→│       ├── analyze.py\n   429→│       └── FINDINGS.md\n   430→├── idea-3-evolutionary-synthesis/ # Deferred (HYPOTHESIS.md only)\n   431→├── problem.md                   # Problem statement\n   432→├── research.md                  # Full research document (WP1)\n   433→└── DECISION_GATE.md             # WP4/5 decision gate\n   434→```\n   435→\n   436→**Dependencies:** Python 3, pandas, scikit-learn, scipy, xgboost\n   437→**Data:** `eval/ground_truth/` (122,752 steps from 16 experiments)\n   438→**Hardware configs:** `model_configs/` (HuggingFace config.json), `hardware_config.json` (H100 specs)\n   439→\n   440→---\n   441→\n   442→## 12. Summary for Future Ideation\n   443→\n   444→**What the data tells us:**\n   445→1. Per-experiment XGBoost with 30 features is 2x better than blackbox (34% vs 70% avg MAPE)\n   446→2. The bottleneck is **feature quality** (missing per-request KV), not model capacity\n   447→3. Global models are structurally impossible without scale normalization\n   448→4. The analytical decomposition is physically correct but data-incomplete\n   449→5. \"General\" workloads are the hardest — high batch composition diversity\n   450→6. Round 1 only modeled `StepTime()` in Python — no Go integration, no queueing/scheduling delays, no KV dynamics, no E2E validation\n   451→\n   452→**What Round 2 should explore:**\n   453→1. Deriving per-request KV features from lifecycle data (`request_metrics/`)\n   454→2. Log-scale or normalized prediction for cross-model generalization\n   455→3. BLIS E2E validation (does 34% per-step MAPE → <10% E2E mean error?)\n   456→4. Simpler models with better features (Ridge/piecewise with per-request KV)\n   457→5. Batch composition clustering for \"general\" workloads\n   458→6. Evolutionary synthesis (Idea 3 h1) if OpenEvolve becomes available\n   459→7. Modeling all 5 `LatencyModel` methods — not just `StepTime()` — with Go integration from the start\n   460→\n   461→**Hard constraints to respect:**\n   462→- Per-model training is mandatory (LOMO fails at 2559%)\n   463→- Features must be computable from `[]*Request` with `ProgressIndex` (Go integration)\n   464→- Prediction latency < 1ms per step\n   465→- Pure-Go implementation (no Python/ONNX runtime)\n   466→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Vx9FActZvVu6PzWLHbXEX2","session_id":"7ea608f4-4aa5-4264-9119-cf38f8fb2f5c","uuid":"944048f0-c970-413e-afcd-d8cdb6dabdfa"}
