{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_bdrk_01Ed6z5XeAch2geBS5cyoYsx","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-opus-4-6","content":[{"type":"text","text":"`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`\n**What this experiment revealed about DES simulation fidelity:**\n\n1. **Two-layer error decomposition is essential.** The 427.8% E2E error from Round 2 decomposed into two independent layers: workload-generation error (responsible for the 31,906% TTFT catastrophe) and step-time prediction error (responsible for the remaining 56% E2E). Without trace replay to separate these layers, the step-time model appeared far worse than it actually was.\n\n2. **Cascading under-prediction is worse than per-step error.** Even though ITL (per-token error) is only 9.5%, E2E error is 56% because each step's slight under-prediction cascades: faster steps → faster queue drain → lower TTFT → lower E2E. This is the M/D/1 queuing effect from DistServe — near capacity, small timing errors produce exponential metric divergence.\n\n3. **The overhead floor needs recalibration.** The 3.9ms floor was calibrated on `step.duration_us` (GPU compute), but real vLLM step cycles include CPU scheduling (scheduler decisions, memory management, CUDA synchronization). Doubling the floor to ~8ms would bring BLIS closer to reality. This is actionable for Ideas 2 and 3.\n`─────────────────────────────────────────────────`\n\nAll three sub-hypotheses for Idea 1 (Trace-Driven Simulation with Lifecycle Replay) have been completed. Here's the summary:\n\n## Experiment Complete: Round 3, Idea 1 — Trace Replay\n\n### Results at a Glance\n\n| Sub-Hypothesis | Status | Key Finding |\n|---|---|---|\n| **H1: Trace replay reduces TTFT** | **SUPPORTED** | TTFT: 31,906% → 78.8% (405x reduction). E2E: 427.8% → 56.2% (7.6x reduction) |\n| **H2: Remaining E2E < 25%** | **REFUTED** | E2E is 56.2%, 0/10 under 25%. BLIS scheduling systematically under-predicts |\n| **H3: Identify workload-spec parameter** | **REFUTED** | All spec parameters match < 1%. Error is in the generation *process*, not parameters |\n\n### What was built\n- `run_experiment.py` — Full experiment runner for all 3 sub-hypotheses\n- Go changes: `--stepml-model` CLI flag + factory dispatch (~22 lines across 3 files)\n- Patch file: `stepml_cli_integration.patch` for reproducibility\n- All Go tests pass (`go test ./...` clean)\n\n### Key Discovery\nThe 31,906% TTFT error was caused by workload *generation*, not parameters. With trace replay, the remaining 56% E2E error is a systematic step-time under-prediction — BLIS completes requests at ~40% of real time because the overhead floor (3.9ms) captures only GPU compute time, missing ~4ms of CPU scheduling overhead per step cycle. This is the new binding constraint for Ideas 2 and 3.\n\n### Artifacts Written\n- `h1-trace-replay/FINDINGS.md` + `summary.json` + `trace_replay_results.csv`\n- `h2-error-attribution/FINDINGS.md` + `summary.json` + `error_attribution.csv`\n- `h3-workload-diagnosis/FINDINGS.md` + `summary.json` + `workload_diagnosis.csv`\n- `FINDINGS_SUMMARY.md` (comprehensive summary with all 9 required sections)"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7ea608f4-4aa5-4264-9119-cf38f8fb2f5c","uuid":"b0e8aeea-f490-4fce-91c4-15aefc3e5a0c"}
